<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONTROVERSIAL BEHAVIORIST B.F. SKINNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Times' obituary of Skinner (Aug. 20) was remarkably well-done. It provided 
a good sense of the life of this dramatically influential psychologist. 
</P>
<P>
There was neither confusion of the baby tender with the Skinner box nor of 
Palov's classical conditioning with operant conditioning, a distinction that 
eluded a national news magazine and a scientific journal. 
</P>
<P>
It tells us something about ourselves that even such fine journalism is no 
protection against a major distortion of one of Skinner's fundamental beliefs: 
that behavior uncaused by heredity and environment, sometimes called free will, 
is a fuzzy mirage. The article informs us that Skinner "argued to the end . . . 
(that) there is little or no free will." "Argued to the end" is a phrase you'd 
expect to find applied to an earlier century to an atheist who died without the 
expected death-bed recantation. In fact, Skinner explained, as have many before 
him, that so-called free will is a misconception. Therefore, he could not 
believe that people might have just a little of it, except in the sense that 
they might have just a little of the misconception. 
</P>
<P>
Skinner did not propose "forsaking individual freedom . . . in favor of 
controlling human behavior to achieve a world free of war," etc. There is 
nothing to forsake but a muddled concept, which is held to because it is 
confused with a meaningful freedom: the freedom to do what one wishes uncoerced 
by others. A clearer understanding will reduce resistance to needed social 
engineering and also sensitize us to the dangers of being subtly manipulated to 
our disadvantage by those using rewards rather than threats. 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD O'CONNELL 
</P>
<P>
Professor of Psychology 
</P>
<P>
Cal State Northridge 
</P>
</TEXT>
