<LENGTH>
<P>
159 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FESTIVAL '90; 
</P>
<P>
SCREENINGS PRESENT PACIFIC RIM CULTURES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sunday 
</P>
<P>
Mana Waka 
</P>
<P>
New Zealand 
</P>
<P>
 Sunday, 8 p.m., Warner Grand, 478 W. 6th St., San Pedro; Tuesday, 8 p.m., 
Melnitz Theater, UCLA 
</P>
<P>
In this fascinating documentary, two filmmakers and a Maori princess 
collaborate across half a century on a poetic celebration of Zealand tribal 
culture. The subject is the waka taua building project: the 1938 construction, 
by Princess Te Puea Herangi's tribe, of a sacred boat. 
</P>
<P>
The footage of this painstaking job, the felling of huge trees, the laborious 
shoreward trek, intricate ceremonial carvings and final glorious launch -- was 
shot by Jim Manley in 1938; ever since, it has rested in the New Zealand Film 
Archive. Director Merata Mita has expertly edited Manley's work, sweetening it 
with an evocative soundtrack. The result has a bit of the monochrome lyricism 
of "Tabu" or "White Shadows in the South Seas," and a unique historical 
perspective. It's a one-of-a-kind experience. MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Series; Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090190-0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 270001 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 1, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 11; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
112 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FESTIVAL '90; 
</P>
<P>
SCREENINGS PRESENT PACIFIC RIM CULTURES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Night Cries 
</P>
<P>
Australia 
</P>
<P>
 Today, noon, AFI, 2021 N. Western Ave., Hollywood; 7 p.m, Warner Grand 
Theatre, 478 W. 6th St., San Pedro 
</P>
<P>
Tracey Moffat's piercing vignette of an aboriginal woman coping in a desert 
cul-de-sac with the nerve-fraying illness of her mother. A mood piece in which 
the Outback is recreated mostly on the soundstage -- in shockingly vivid 
primary colors and images that suggest a Douanier Rousseau painting. 
Cobalt-blue skies, painted backdrops, a purringly ingratiating gospel singer, 
flashbacks to the ocean and a present full of sweat and misery -- Moffat weaves 
it all together with erratic but sometimes genuine power. MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
